  <div class="topic">
    <h4>Step 1: Folder Structure</h4>

    <p>As you know by now, code is just text that the computer can read. We save this code in normal, eveyday files that are stored in a series of folders. Go ahead and decide where you'll be saving all of our code for our bootcamp. It's a good idea to create a folder called <strong>code</strong> where you store everything and to create sub-folders for more speific work. Here is an example. These are all folders</p>

    <p>-<strong>home</strong></p>
    <p>--<strong>code</strong></p>
    <p>---<strong>bootcamp</strong></p>
    <p>----<strong>week-1</strong></p>
    <p>----<strong>week-2</strong></p>
    <p>----<strong>week-3</strong></p>
    <p>----<strong>week-4</strong></p>

    <p>Go ahead and create you own folder structure now and decide where you'll store the code your write for the bootcamp.</p>
  </div>

  <hr>

  <div class="topic">
    <h4>Step 2: Command Line Navigation</h4>

    <p>Until now, you might have used "finder" or the "start" menu on your computer to navigate through files and folders. As a developer, you'll be using the <strong>command-line</strong> quite a bit, so it will be much easier to navigate folders from there.</p> 

    <p>Go ahead and open your <strong>command-line</strong> now: if you're using a Mac this is called <strong>Terminal</strong> or <strong>iTerm</strong>, and if you're using a Windows Machine it's called <strong>Command Prompt</strong>. It will look something like this:</p>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-16-at-12.18.26-PM.png"></img>

    <p>By default, your command-line will open inside of your "home folder". Let's see what's inside. If you're using a <strong>Mac</strong> type in the following, then hit enter:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">ls</pre>

    <p>If you're using a <strong>Windows</strong>, type in:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">dir</pre>

    <p>Now you should see a list of your files and folders. Something like this:</p>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-16-at-12.25.44-PM.png"></img>

    <p>Now to navigate forward into a folder you'll type in "cd" + "folder_name". For example, if I wanted get into my <strong>code</strong> folder, I'd type this:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">cd code</pre>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-16-at-2.55.14-PM.png"></img>

    <p>Once again I can list all the file/folders in there by typing (mac):</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">cd code</pre>

    <p>Or (windows):</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">dir</pre>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-16-at-2.59.02-PM.png"></img>

    <p>Now to back-up one, I would type (both mac and windows):</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">cd ..</pre>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-16-at-3.00.35-PM.png"></img>
  </div>

  <hr>

  <div class="topic">
    <h4>Step 3: Creating a New Project</h4>

    <p>Using the commands we learned above, navigate to the folder where you want to create today's project (for example: <strong>code</strong>><strong></strong > <strong>bootcamp</strong> > <strong>week-1</strong>). Once you're there, type in:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">mkdir portfolio</pre>

    <p>This will create a new folder called "portfolio". <strong>mkdir</strong> means, "make directory" and is used for creating folders. Now we will create two files inside this folder. First "cd" into it by typing:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">cd portfolio</pre>

    <p>Now to create our new files we will type:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">touch index.html</pre>
    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">touch style.css</pre>

    <p>Or if you're using a windows machine:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">fsutil file createnew index.html 0</pre>
    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">fsutil file createnew style.css 0</pre>

    <p>Now if you type <strong>ls</strong>, you should see your new files:</p>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-16-at-3.17.19-PM.png"></img>

    <p>Finally, let's open these up inside of sublime by typing in this (for Mac):</p>
    <p>Note: some of you may not have this command availabile and will need to open the folder from Sublime's menu via <c>file:Open...</c></p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">subl .</pre>

    <p>Or this for Windows:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">subl.exe</pre>

    <p>This will open your project in Sublime. Remember that you must be at the "root" of your project (inside the folder) to open it in Sublime.</p>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-16-at-3.23.53-PM.png"></img>
  </div>

