  <div class="topic">
    <h4>Step 5: CSS Setup</h4>

    <p>Nothing too impressive for now, but let's add some color in here. For this we of course need the help of CSS. The first think we need to do is make our HTML file aware of our CSS file. To do, we will add the following HTML inside of the <strong>head</strong> tag:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">  <span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">head</span>></span>
    <span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">link</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">rel</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"stylesheet"</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">type</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"text/css"</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">href</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"style.css"</span>></span>
    <span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">title</span>>&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">title</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">head</span>></span>
</pre>

    <p>We've added a <strong>link</strong> tag with 3 <strong>attributes</strong>: "rel" (relationship), "type" and "href" (hypertext reference). When we're linking CSS files to our HTML file, all of these attributes will have these values, but the value of "href" will always be the filepath from our HTML file to our CSS file. Since both <strong>index.html</strong> and <strong>style.css</strong> are in the same folder, we just write <strong>style.css</strong>.</p>

    <p>Now add the following CSS inside of <strong>style.css</strong>:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#cda869">h1</span> {
  <span style="color:#c5af75">color</span>: <span style="color:#cf6a4c">red</span>;
}
</pre>
    <p>Now, our H1 is red!</p>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-16-at-3.49.09-PM.png"></img>

